In this update:
[1] Estonia, ovine, clinical cases
[2] Sweden, ovine, clinical cases

******
[1] Estonia, ovine, clinical cases
Date: Wed 16 Jan 2013
Source: Flutrackers [machine trans. from http://www.postimees.ee/1105170/vorumaa-ja-hiiumaa-lammastel-tuvastati-schmallenbergi-viirus/, edited]
http://www.flutrackers.com/forum/showthread.php?p=481177#post481177


Sheep fetuses affected by the Schmallenberg virus, which had recently spread in Europe, have been recorded in Vorumaa and Hiiumaa; this has been confirmed by the Veterinary and Food Board.

"Laboratory studies of aborted fetuses from sheep farms in Hiiumaa and Vorumaa have confirmed infection by the Schmallenberg virus [SBV]," said Maarja Kristian, Head, Food and Veterinary Office, Division of Animal Health and Animal Feed.

Kristian says this is a viral disease that does not present a very high risk and is not particularly dangerous.

"Quarantine or restrictions or limitations are imposed," said Kristian. "This is a new virus disease in Europe; there is no treatment, and vaccine is not available yet."

Kristian said that such SBV cases have not been identified previously [in Estonia]. These cases were found due to the farmer's information about an increase in the number of abortions in the herd.

"It is primarily a disease of sheep and goats, which can occur in cattle," explained Kristian. Abortions occur in pregnant females, and fetuses are aborted with deformities."

--
