******
[2] Sweden, ovine, clinical cases
Date: Wed 16 Jan 2013
Source: SVT (Swedish public service television) [machine trans. edited]
http://www.svt.se/nyheter/regionalt/svtsormland/elakt-virus-smittar-far


Many sheep breeders have been affected by the aggressive Schmallenberg virus, with deformed and stillborn lambs.

The virus is spread by midges, and pregnant ewes that were infected by the virus in late summer last year [2012] currently give birth to deformed and stillborn lambs.

The virus in present in Sodermanland and Gotland, and a suspected case has been reported from Ostergotland.

[A video showing affected lambs is available at the source URL.]

--
Communicated by:
Gert van der Hoek
Senior Moderator
FluTrackers.com

[A ProMED-mail HealthMap for Sweden is available at http://healthmap.org/r/20NO.]

[SBV is known to have already caused clinical cases (abortions/still-births/congenital malformations) in large and/or small ruminants in the following 16 European countries: Germany, The Netherlands, Belgium, the United Kingdom, France, Italy, Luxembourg, Spain, Denmark, Switzerland, Ireland, Northern Ireland, Finland, Sweden, Estonia and the Czech Republic (Information on cases in the Czech Republic is available at http://tinyurl.com/b8utwgl, dated 21 Dec 2012, thanks to Sabine Zentis for the missed source.). In addition, Norway, Austria, and Poland have detected antibodies in domestic ruminants. In Norway, the virus has been initially detected in biting midges; the official information on positive SBV serology (in cattle) is available at http://tinyurl.com/bh8astc.

The speed and spatial dissemination of SBV in Europe exceed that demonstrated by BTV-8 (2006-2010). The detailed economic and international-trade implications of SBV are yet to be thoroughly assessed.

Last year [2012], the EU allocated 3 million euros [USD 4 million] for scientific studies on SBV in 7 member-countries. The studies were to be co-financed by the commission at 50 percent of eligible costs from 1 Apr 2012 - 31 Dec 2013, details at http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/schmallenberg_virus/index_en.htm.

SBV is one of the issues on the agenda of the upcoming International Meeting on Emerging Diseases and Surveillance (IMED) in Vienna, 15-18 Feb 2013. - Mod.AS]
